Subject:Re: [Antenna-discussion] 1/2-wave vertical really needs a ground
	plane?
Ward

Yes, well I was being a stickler but I was using 'dipole' in more of
the original sense of equal and opposite charges, as is the case with
a centre-fed dipole.  I guess things like a Windom are also described
as dipoles now so we must go with the flow.

The main point was that a vertical dipole that does not connect to the
ground does not need ground wires.

Alan G3NOQ



On 8 November 2012 16:06, ward <ward2@ussu.us> wrote:
> Alan:
>    I hate to fall into the 'stickler' category but I feel
> inclined to at this point because it raises an important
> point.
>    There are plenty of 'dipoles' which are not centre
> fed; the Carolina Windom being a prime example.
> Resonant, half wave dipoles can be fed nearly
> anywhere including so close to the end as to appear
> end fed=85..
>
> I use the term 'dipole' to convey the RF currents on
> the wire, not the location of the feed point.  Indeed,
> I'd go so far as to say there needn't be an explicit feed
> point.  For example, a Yagi-Uda director is a dipole
> but has no feed 'point'.
>
> Again, sorry to fall into the stickler category.
>
> ward
>
> On Nov 8, 2012, at 3:50 AM, boswell alan wrote:
>
> Ward
>
> To address your point literally, a halfwave vertical 'dipole' is fed
> at its centre, by definition.  Assuming the lower end is above ground,
> radials are not needed.  That is because the ground currents
> associated with groundwave propagation are radial, so there is nowhere
> for them to flow at the point directly under the antenna, therefore
> they must be zero there.  At other points in the near field region the
> currents are not zero but are much less than with a ground-based
> antenna.
>
> That is easily confirmed by a quick NEC run.
>
> Alan G3NOQ
>
>
>
>
>
>
> On 7 November 2012 15:14, ward <ward2@ussu.us> wrote:
>> As seems often to be the case, this discussion is getting away from
>> the original question and I suppose I'm at fault as much as anyone.
>>
>> The original question concerned the need for radials for a half
>> wave, vertical dipole antenna.
>>
>> There were several responses indicating that yes, radials were
>> absolutely necessary.
>>
>> One of the responses showed that you needed a small 'counterpoise'
>> which was around 1/20th of a wavelength long.  This was needed
>> to provide the 'second terminal' of the feed line so a to balance
>> feed line currents. There are arguments about the mechanism, but
>> generally folks agree you need this small counterpoise or the
>> feedline will fill in.  The currents are quite small.
>>    I generally think of this as an extremely off-center-fed,
>> resonant, half wave dipole.  We all have different thinking models.
>>
>>
>> Another response referenced the traditional 'you need scads
>> of radials to carry the huge, RF return currents'.  This article
>> discuss MONOPOLES which DO have huge currents flowing
>> in the 'radials'.  These are different beasts.
>>
>> So, the original answer is: you do need a relatively small
>> 'counterpoise' to balance the feed line currents but you don't
>> need radial fields in the ground or big radials lofted in the air.
>>
>> ward
>>
>>
>> On Nov 7, 2012, at 4:24 AM, boswell alan wrote:
>>
>> Ward
>>
>> An end-fed halfwave can be resonant but it only has one terminal - the
>> end of the wire.  Some other structure is needed to connect the other
>> side of the feeder to.  That other piece is also part of the antenna.
>>
>> If the end-fed is fed from the centre of a coax cable, the current on
>> the inner side of the sheath wraps round and travels back down on the
>> outer of the cable, so it becomes a radiating wire :)
>>
>> Alan G3NOQ
>>
>>
>>
>>
>>
>>
